\begin_layout Standard
In a landmark paper, Frank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fetter1901thepassing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 critically examined land-rent theory at the turn of the twentieth century.
 Alfred Marshall's 
\emph on
Principles of Economics 
\emph default
was widely acclaimed and accepted at the time, and since it expanded on
 the then-dominant view of land rent, Professor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "fetter1901thepassing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 used it
\emph on
 
\emph default
as an authoritative statement of what he called, the 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

conventional view
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 of land rent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By comparison, commentators on land-rent today are seriously handicapped.
 The subject has been largely neglected for roughly the past twenty-five
 years, and whatever work on land-rent theory has been done recently is
 diffuse and in disarray: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Land rent theory does not have one coherent and widely accepted theoretical
 corpus, but consists of a variety of different conceptualizations, even
 of its central categories
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "234"
key "jager2003urbanland"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Beyond the distinction between mainstream, neoclassical economics and heterodox
 approaches, one cannot even identify a small number of competing candidate
 theories for purposes of comparison.
 And certainly a contemporary commentator has no authoritative text equivalent
 to Marshall's 
\emph on
Principles
\emph default
 from which to draw authoritative statements about land rent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nonetheless, several authors have recently written histories of land-rent
 theory, and at least these anglophone histories share much in common.
 Even more than their actual content and details, their approach to the
 history of land-rent theory hardly varies.
 They share a common, and not altogether approbative, historiography.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See note 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fn:histories"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for examples of such histories.
 In one, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "48"
key "haila2016urbanland"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 says, 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

The history of this [land-rent] theory is not a story of progress towards
 a better understanding of land rent but rather an adaptation to emerging
 social problems, like poverty, taxes, speculation, or high land prices.
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 This suggests that land-rent theory has most often developed in a 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

targeted
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 manner, as discussed above.
 Given that recent histories of land-rent theory claim the subject has been
 neglected for over two decades and is decrepit, these histories can hardly
 be ones of unequivocal scientific progress, in which later developments
 are improvements on earlier ones.
 But neither is the conventional historiography of land rent terribly critical,
 and the common practice of organizing histories chronologically without
 much critical comment creates an underlying sense of theoretical progress
 and positive evolution, or at least one that was unavoidable.
 This practice is so common with land-rent theory that it is even hard to
 imagine alternatives historiographical approaches, such as focusing on
 biography or emphasizing social problems (and conflicts) Haila briefly
 mentions.
 Compare this with the 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

Whig
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 history that dominates mainstream economics, the product of a historiography
 that writes history from the standpoints of historical victors and treats
 the past as prologue to a self-glorified present 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "freeman2014samuelsons,goodacre2014thewilliam"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By examining this 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

conventional historiography,
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 its limitations, and its shared tacit assumptions, I intend to open up
 broader scope for a rejuvenated land-rent theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In her landmark review of land-rent theory, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "haila1990thetheory"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 interprets land-rent theory as answering one or more of three main questions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
