\end_layout

\end_inset

How does rent emerge?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Who are its agents, and what are their behavioral patterns and social relations?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is rent's economic role?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the conventional historiography these questions have become a common
 device for interpreting and evaluating land-rent theory and for organizing
 historical narratives, either explicitly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "ward2016theshitty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or implicitly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g., "
key "jager2003urbanland"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 But to cover the entire theoretical landscape, the questions are themselves
 necessarily broad.
 This breadth creates an 
\emph on
illusion
\emph default
 of comprehesiveness, but in fact it makes the questions have a certain
 vagueness, which in turn obscures important omissions and unrecognized
 assumptions.
 For example, the first question covers now-familiar 
\emph on
mechanisms
\emph default
 by which rent comes into existence â€“ differential rent, absolute rent,
 etc., but taken literally it also covers long geo-historical processes such
 as how the Roman practice of compensating soldiers with land, eventually
 providing the basis for feudal landownership and rent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "cf. e.g.,"
key "coats2013thecalculus"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Yet considerations of this second sort are completely missing from the
 conventional historiography.
 Similarly, the third question covers the entirerty of economic ramifications
 of rent, but in actual practice the conventional historiography reduces
 this to rather narrow economic functions, such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coordination,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which themselves are often under-theorized and tacitly functionalist.
 While the literature as a whole does not always completely ignore other
 economic roles â€“ such as land rent's role in business cycles and crises;
 in wages, unemployment, and income distribution; or in globalization, finance,
 and international trade â€“ the vagueness of the question solicits answers
 that can be completely irrelevant to 
\emph on
more
\emph default
 
\emph on
specific
\emph default
 economic roles such as these.
 Even worse, it creates space for land-rent theories that go beyond having
 nothing so say about such things and are demonstrably wrong when confronted
 with such economic issues.
 The following sections explore these lines of criticism in more depth.
\end_layout

