\end_inset

Western-Modern Parochialism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, consider the conventional historiography's treatment of time and
 space, history and geography.
 Virtually all contemporary histories of land-rent theory draw exclusively
 from Western Europe or North America, and primarily use anglophone sources
 dating back not much earlier than James Anderson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "anderson1777aninquiry"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the Scottish Enlightenment (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
after "3;"
key "ward2016theshitty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tian2014property"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This timing is by no means innocent.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "198"
key "jevons1871thetheory"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

