\begin_layout Standard
Land rent dates back at least to classical antiquity and certainly did not
 originate in early modernity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ellickson_ancient_1995,williams_leasing_2011,jakab_property_2015"
posttextlist "williams_leasing_2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Neither was its ancient practice only in the West, although comparative
 geo-historical research is still in its infancy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bavel_institutional_2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In 2016, archeologists reported that in the ruins of Teos, a Greek colony
 i
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "haila1990thetheory"
literal "false"

\end_inset

n present-day western Turkey, they had found the oldest known rental agreement
 for land 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dogan_news_agency_centuries-old_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The 2,200-year-old agreement contains numerous conditions, such as the
 tenant having the right to use slaves who came with the land, the landlords
 having the right to access an alter on the land three times per year for
 religious purposes, and many punishments if the tenant violated the terms
 of the lease.
 
\emph on
The New York Post
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "li_renting_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ran a story about the discovery, making it sound as if renting a place
 over two millennia ago was no different from renting an apartment in Brooklyn
 today.
 This this is gross distortion and a good example of a methodological point
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "42"
key "marx1986themethod"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 makes in criticizing 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

those economists who see in all forms of society the bourgeois forms.
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 In ancient Greece land was overwhelmingly the main form of wealth and the
 primary means of exploitation, through extraction of both direct labor,
 products of labor, and money; the majority of the population lacked either
 the right or the mean to own land and was exploited through land 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "croix_class_1997,foxhall_dependent_1990"
posttextlist "foxhall_dependent_1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marx's methodological point quoted above is embedded in a larger one that
 deserves more attention.
 He writes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Bourgeois society is the most developed and many-faceted historical 
\lang british
organisation
\lang english
 of production.
 The categories which express its relations, an understanding of its structure,
 therefore, provide, at the same time, an insight into the structure and
 the relations of production of all previous forms of society ....
 Some [components] of these remains [from earlier forms] are still dragged
 along within bourgeois society unassimilated, while elements which previously
 were barely indicated have developed and attained their full significance,
 etc.
 The anatomy of man is a key to the anatomy of the ape.
 On the other hand, indications of higher forms in the lower species of
 animals can only be understood when the higher forms themselves are already
 known.
 Bourgeois economy thus provides a key to that of antiquity, etc.
 ...
 One can understand tribute, tithe, etc., if one knows rent.
 But they must not be treated as identical.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "42"
key "marx1986themethod"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here he assumes a teleology of historical temporality, with successive forms
 of social organization being more developed and complex.
 In retrospect, such optimism, if one can call it that, seems hardly warranted
 and remarkably undialectical.
 Surely the structure and relations of previous forms of society, and of
 geographically separate forms of society, can also provide insight into
 the structure and relations of present-day Western society.
 And this applies to both transitive and intransitive dimensions of knowledge
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bhaskar1978arealist"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: investigations into earlier and/or geographically distinct forms of society,
 using both present-day categories and those of the other society â€“ such
 as Marx's proposed study of tribute and tithes â€“ have the potential to
 provide insights not only into the structure and relations of these other
 societies and their own conceptions of themselves (e.g., of tribute, tithe,
 etc.), but also into the structure and relations of present-day society
 and into the present-day conceptions (e.g., of rent) used to comprehend the
 present.
 Furthermore, at a time when human civilization seems to be careening towards
 some combination of political, economic, and ecological calamity, broadening
 the scope of land-rent research beyond Western modernity holds the promise
 of inspiring new models and policies that may stave off the apocalypse.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Haila's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "haila2016urbanland"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 recent study of Singapore is a step in the right direction, although I
 would appreciate a longer history than Haila's brief one, which starts
 in the late colonial period.
 A review of landownership and rent practices in ancient areas dominated
 by Indian and Chinese culture and states, tracing them to the present,
 would help identify the historical roots of contemporary Singapore and
 distinguish what is indigenous from what is imported, what is traditional
 from what is modern.
 I would also welcome more comparative work to help sort through these thorny
 threads.
 Haila's synchronic analysis would benefit from a complementary diachronic,
 comparative one.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "aalbers00000aconversation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for an interesting conversation touching on such issues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Regarding Marx, like other nineteenth-century theories of land rent, which
 deal mainly with agricultural land, Marx's own theories of land-rent are
 for the most part either no longer significant or no longer valid.
 See below.
 Nonetheless, he continues to be an exemplar of how to think of land rent.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The terms 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

history
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

historiography
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 have some ambiguity here and need clarification.
 The distinction between the two runs This terminology is complicated, in
 part, by the fact that the intransitive object of knowledge â€“ the world
 â€“ has a 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

layered
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 ontology consisting of the real, actual, and empirical.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

Real
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 refers to the things comprising the world, their structures, causal powers,
 and liabilities.
 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

Actual
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 and refers to the things and events that happen in the world, typically
 due to the exercise of one or more real causal power.
 And 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

empirical
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

actual
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

; it refers to actual events human actors experience, whether they consciously
 observe the experience or not.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Human history is intransitive in that it is what it is, and no retrospective
 historical account can change history.
 While 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

real history
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 resides beneath and contains 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

actual history,
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

actual history
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 only occurs once and may or may not be 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

empirical history.
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
History is always geographical, but here I use the more common term, 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

history,
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 rather than a more cumbersome one, such as 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

geo-history,
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 that may do more justice to the spatiality of human existence.
 As an example of the distinctions between real, actual, and empirical history,
 consider the 2016 U.S.
 presidential election.
 How much influence did foreign hacking have on voters? Social media, hacking,
 etc.
 are all real and have causal powers, and if history actually could repeat
 itself, then perhaps the hacking would have been publicly exposed and the
 election would have had a different outcome.
 And, as ongoing investigations demonstrate, everything that happened during
 the election has not yet become empirically observable, some potentially
 observable things may remain hidden, and others â€“ such as voters' individual
 thought processes â€“ simply cannot possibly be experienced observed retrospectiv
ely by a scientific (or legal) investigator.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 But in the English language 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

history
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 has another meaning, such as Gibbon's 
\emph on
The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire
\emph default
.
 Here 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

history
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 refers to a particular (transitive) account.
 Partly to avoid confusion between these two senses of 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

history,
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 I use 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

history
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

historiography.
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 The latter is squarely in the transitive sphere and refers to particular
 approaches to constructing and relating accounts of particular (intransitive)
 histories.
 Nonetheless, a certain amount of ambiguity, particularly regarding 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

history,
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 but hopefully the context will make my meaning clear.
 But this is not the only reason I focus on historiography.
 Certain accounts of the history of land-rent theory have much in common,
 and by lumping them together I aim to expose their common limits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, despite roughly twenty-five years of neglect, the study of
 land rent is arguably more common economic geography and urban geography
 than any other academic fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A Specter Named Karl
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contemporary scholarship on land-rent and closely related topics â€“ such
 as land value, land use, residential location and segregation, etc.
 â€“ can be found in traditional social-science disciplines, multidisciplinary
 fields like urban studies or development studies, and mixed professional/applie
d/social-scientific fields like spatial planning.
 The Vietnam War was the biggest debacle of the Cold War and by the early
 1970s was accompanied by a massive anti-war movement, which not coincidentally
 coincided with the first noticable signs of what would be an extended period
 of general economic malaise punctuated by episodic economic crises and
 continuing to the present.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For examples of various accounts of this malaise and explanations for it
 see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "foster1997thelong,dumenil2002theprofit,brenner2006theeconomics,krugman2008thereturn,beitel2009therate,gordon2017therise"
posttextlist "foster1997thelong	dumenil2002theprofit"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The bigger point is how this context influenced a generation of scholars
 in terms of their interests and approaches.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In this context, interest in Marxist thought spread throughout academic
 fields focused on society.
 But this was very uneven.
 Marxist political economy came to dominate economic geography, so much
 so that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

geographical political economy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 became a common label for the field 
